CJS 2026-04-01
  TODO: Implement composite key methylation schema - Modify the commaData schema
  with a composite mod_type-motif key. This is the core methylation ontology to
  automatically separate analyses by: adenine methylation at a GATC motif arises
  by a different biological process than cytosine methylation at CCWGG motifs;
  furthermore, cytosine methylation calls at GATC motifs is likely spurious and
  we want to make sure they can never be included in intended 6mA at GATC
  calculations. Retain mod_type and motif columns so users can filter by them,
  but by default all analyses should be run separately by mod_type-motif groups.
  Call the key what you want, something like "mod_context," and format it like
  "6mA_GATC" or "4mC_CCWGG" or whatever. Also note that 21839 mod_types are 4mC.

CJS 2026-04-01
  TODO: Implement a way when constructing the commaData object to input expected
  modification type--motif pairs. The default should be "all" so that nothing
  is filtered, but from my experience I know I only want 6mA at GATC sites and
  5mC at CCWGG sites, and a 6mA at CCWGG or 5mC at GATC is likely spurious. In
  the future, I think an option to identify "real" methylated motifs using
  something like MicrobeMod would be a good idea; I don't want to implement this
  now, but keep it in mind when developing the schema for this so commaData can
  be extended later. For now, something like a named list would be good to have
  like list(6mA = c("GATC", "ACCACC"), 5mC = "CCWGG") as there are always more
  motifs than types of methylation, so then it will filter the object to keep
  only 6mA at GATC and ACCACC, as well as 5mC at CCWGG.
